I have a simple C++ program that goes as follows

```
#include "mxnet-cpp/MxNetCpp.h"

int main()
{
	using namespace mxnet::cpp;
	
	Symbol data = Symbol::Variable("data");
	Symbol conv1_w("conv1_w"), conv1_b("conv1_b");

	Symbol conv1 = Convolution("conv1", data, conv1_w, conv1_b, Shape(5, 5), 20);
	Symbol tanh1 = Activation("tanh1", conv1, ActivationActType::kTanh);
	
	return 0;
}
```

However, when I ran the program. I got a segmentation fault. According to `gdb`, the call stack goes as follows

```
#0  0x00000000006cbf9b in NNGetOpInfo ()
#1  0x000000000042ab32 in MXSymbolGetAtomicSymbolInfo ()
#2  0x00000000004136ad in mxnet::cpp::Operator::Operator(std::__cxx11::basic_string<char, std::char_traits<char>, std::allocator<char> > const&) ()
#3  0x0000000000414c1a in mxnet::cpp::Convolution(std::__cxx11::basic_string<char, std::char_traits<char>, std::allocator<char> > const&, mxnet::cpp::Symbol, mxnet::cpp::Symbol, mxnet::cpp::Symbol, mxnet::cpp::Shape, unsigned int, mxnet::cpp::Shape, mxnet::cpp::Shape, mxnet::cpp::Shape, unsigned int, unsigned long, bool, mxnet::cpp::ConvolutionCudnnTune, bool, mxnet::cpp::ConvolutionLayout) ()
#4  0x0000000000410499 in main ()
```

I have also tried different types of computation (`FullyConnected`, etc.), but whatever I tried, I always get a segmentation fault from `NNGetOpInfo()`. Why is this and how can I solve it?

Calling `bind` on custom ops that don't have inputs, but auxiliary data segfaults:

```python
import mxnet as mx
import numpy as np


class Op(mx.operator.CustomOp):
    pass


@mx.operator.register("custom_op")
class Prop(mx.operator.CustomOpProp):
    def list_arguments(self):
        return []
    
    def list_outputs(self):
        return ['out']
    
    def list_auxiliary_states(self):
        return ['value']

    def infer_shape(self, in_shape):
        return [], [(2, 2)], [(2, 2)]
    
    def infer_type(self, in_shape):
        return [], [np.float32], [np.float32]
    
    def create_operator(self, ctx, shapes, dtypes):
        return Op()
    

foo = mx.symbol.Custom(name='foo', op_type='custom_op')
data = mx.nd.ones((2, 2))

foo.bind(mx.cpu(), [], aux_states={'foo_value': data})
```

According to lldb the segfault happens in `mxnet::op::custom::CreateState`, somewhere before the call to `ostream` in L242, so in this region:

https://github.com/apache/incubator-mxnet/blob/974ac1758765291337129f546434993376eae687/src/operator/custom/custom.cc#L228-L240

My guess is that `num_args` counts only the number of arguments, but excludes the auxiliary inputs, while `in_shape` and `in_type` counts all of them. If so, the assignment in L235 is illegal, because `params.num_args == 0`.

When using e.g. WindowedStatistics with a time window/number of slice combination that results in a sliceDuration of less than 662 ms(currently) index calculation in Windowed.getCurrentIndex() fails because System.currentTimeMillis()/662 > Integer.MAX_VALUE and casting it to int produces unpredictable results. 

"Best case" is that getCurrentIndex() returns a negative value (as happened to me), causing an ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException because the whole code in sync() is skipped and index will remain at the initial value of -1.

Simple fix, should just be like this:

    protected long getCurrentIndex() {
      return clock.nowMillis() / sliceDuration;
    }

